  [4]
 It's just that virtually all of that value =E2=80=94=C2=A0more than 99% of=
 it =E2=80=94=C2=A0belongs to its creditors. UBS will take over Credit Suis=
se=E2=80=99s hundreds of billions of assets and use them to pay Credit Suis=
se=E2=80=99s hundreds of billions of liabilities, and there's the tiniest s=
liver =E2=80=94=C2=A0about $3 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0left for its sharehold=
ers. That $3 billion is pretty much rounding error on the value of Credit S=
uisse; it could just as well have been $5 billion, or $1 billion, or a Tobl=
erone bar. The value and mechanics of this deal don=E2=80=99t depend that m=
uch on the=C2=A0price for the equity, as you can tell by the fact that UBS=
=C2=A0tripled=C2=A0that price in the course of a few hours.=C2=A0
It really could just as well have been zero, but it is polite to give the s=
hareholders something, a little consolation prize on their way out the door=
. The dynamics are:
=09You want shareholders to get something so that the board of Credit Suiss=
e can feel okay about agreeing to the deal, rather than making=C2=A0trouble=
 and trying to hold out for something better.=C2=A0=09You want shareholders=
 to get something so that they don=E2=80=99t make=C2=A0legal=C2=A0trouble, =
trying to find some legal way to block the deal. (My Bloomberg Opinion coll=
eague Shuli Ren   writes: =E2=80=9CRegulators might have just given Credit =
Suisse=E2=80=99s equity owners some sweeteners so they don=E2=80=99t go to =
court and overturn the merger.=E2=80=9D)=09You want shareholders to get som=
ething so that they are more willing to support the combined bank, and the =
banking system generally, after the merger. If you make Saudi National Bank=
