After the 2008 financial crisis, European banks issued a lot of what are ca=
lled =E2=80=9Cadditional tier 1 capital securities,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cco=
ntingent convertibles,=E2=80=9D or AT1s or CoCos. The way an AT1 works is l=
ike this:
=09It is a bond, has a fixed face amount, and pays regular interest.=C2=A0=
=09It is perpetual =E2=80=94=C2=A0the bank never has to pay it back =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but the bank can pay it back after five years, and generally does.=
=09If the bank=E2=80=99s common equity tier 1 capital ratio =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
a measure of its regulatory capital =E2=80=94=C2=A0ffalls below 7%, then th=
e AT1 is=C2=A0written down to zero:=C2=A0It never needs to be paid back; it=
 just goes away completely.

This =E2=80=94=C2=A0a =E2=80=9C7% trigger permanent write-down AT1=E2=80=9D=
 =E2=80=94 is not the only way for an AT1 to work, though it is the way tha=
t Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s AT1s worked. Some AT1s have different triggers. S=
ome AT1s=C2=A0convert into common stock when the trigger is hit, instead of=
 being written down to zero; others are   temporarily=C2=A0written down (th=
ey stop paying interest) when the trigger is hit, but can bounce back if th=
e equity recovers. (Here is a 2013  primer on CoCos from the Bank for Inter=
national Settlements.)=C2=A0
These securities are, basically, a trick. To=C2=A0investors, they seem like=
 bonds: They pay interest, get paid back in five years, feel pretty safe. T=
o=C2=A0regulators,=C2=A0they seem like equity: If the bank runs into troubl=
e, it can raise capital by zeroing the AT1s. If investors think they are bo=
nds and regulators think they are equity, somebody is wrong. The investors =
are wrong.
In particular, investors seem to think that AT1s are=C2=A0senior=C2=A0to eq=
uity, and that the common stock needs to go to zero before the AT1s suffer =
any losses. But this is not quite right. You can tell=C2=A0because the whol=
e point of the AT1s is that they=C2=A0go to zero if the common equity tier =
1 capital ratio falls below 7%. Like, imagine a bank:
=09It has $1 billion of assets (also $1 billion of regulatory risk-weighted=
 assets).
  [6]

=09It has $100 million of common equity (also $100 million of regulatory co=
mmon equity tier 1 capital).=09It has a 10% CET1 capital ratio.=09It also h=
as $50 million of AT1s with a 7% write-down trigger, and $850 million of mo=
re senior liabilities.

This bank runs into trouble and the value of its assets falls to $950 milli=
on. What happens? Well, under the very straightforward terms of the AT1s =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0not some weird fine print in the back of the prospectus, but=
=C2=A0right in the name =E2=80=9C7% CET1 trigger write-down AT1=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0this is what happens:
=09It has $950 million of assets and $50 million of common equity, for a CE=
T1 ratio of 5.3%.=09This is below 7%, so the AT1s are triggered and written=
 down to zero.=09Now it has $950 million of assets, $850 million of liabili=
ties, and thus $100 million of shareholders=E2=80=99 equity.=09Now it has a=
 CET1 ratio of 10.5%: The writedown of the AT1s has restored the bank=E2=80=
=99s equity capital ratios.

This, again, is very explicitly the whole thing that the AT1 is supposed to=
 do,=C2=A0this is its main function, this is the AT1 working exactly as adv=
ertised. But notice that in this simple example the bank has $950 million o=
f assets, $850 million of liabilities and $100 million of shareholders=E2=
=80=99 equity. This means that=C2=A0the common stock still has value. The c=
ommon shareholders still own shares worth $100 million, even as the AT1s ar=
e now permanently worth zero.
The AT1s are junior to the common stock. Not all the time, and there are sc=
enarios (instant descent into bankruptcy) where the AT1s get paid ahead of =
the common. But the most basic function=C2=A0of the AT1=C2=A0is to go to ze=
ro while the bank is a going concern with positive equity value, meaning th=
at its function is to go to zero before the common stock does.
Credit Suisse has issued a bunch of AT1s over the years; as of last week it=
 had about CHF 16 billion outstanding. Here is  a prospectus for one of the=
m, a $2 billion US dollar 7.5% AT1 issued in 2018. =E2=80=9C7.500 per cent.=
 Perpetual Tier 1 Contingent Write-down Capital Notes,=E2=80=9D they are ca=
lled.
In UBS=E2=80=99s deal to buy Credit Suisse, shareholders are getting someth=
ing (about CHF 3 billion worth of Credit Suisse shares) and Credit Suisse=
=E2=80=99s AT1 holders are getting nothing: The Credit Suisse AT1 securitie=
s are getting zeroed. This is not, to be clear, exactly because Credit Suis=
se=E2=80=99s CET1 capital fell below 7%; instead, there is a separate claus=
e of the AT1s allowing them to be zeroed if the bank=E2=80=99s regulator de=
cides that zeroing them is =E2=80=9Can essential requirement to prevent CSG=
 from becoming insolvent, bankrupt or unable to pay a material part of its =
debts as they fall due.=E2=80=9D
  [7]
=C2=A0Plus, in a situation like this, the banking regulators get to do a ce=
rtain amount of ad hoc stuff, and they do. (They got rid of the shareholder=
 vote on the deal!) Zeroing the AT1s while preserving a little value for th=
e common does seem to have been done in an ad hoc way; my point is just tha=
t it follows very logically from the terms and function of the AT1s.=C2=A0
