<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is sometimes useful to think that the share=
holders of a bank are not its owners; they are just renting it from its cre=
ditors. Schematically, a bank borrows a bunch of money from depositors and =
other creditors and uses the money to make loans and buy securities and do =
other risky investments. If the investments end up being worth more than th=
e deposits, the shareholders keep what=E2=80=99s left. If the investments e=
nd up being worth less than the deposits then, uh, that=E2=80=99s bad. Then=
 the shareholders don=E2=80=99t own the bank anymore, for one thing, but th=
at=E2=80=99s really the least of your problems. The real problem is that=C2=
=A0<em>the depositors can=E2=80=99t lose money</em>; the banking system rel=
ies on bank deposits being usable as money. =E2=80=9CBanks are speculative =
investment funds grafted on top of critical infrastructure,=E2=80=9D Matt K=
lein <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30897493.2584=
33/aHR0cHM6Ly90aGVvdmVyc2hvb3QuY28vcC90aG91Z2h0cy1vbi10aGUtYmFuay1iYWlsb3V0=
cw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6d3cd018" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> wrote last week</a>. The lia=
bilities (deposits, etc.)=C2=A0are the critical infrastructure; the assets =
(loans, securities) are the speculative investment fund. The bank is a mach=
ine for <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30897493.2=
58433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtM=
TcvYmlnLWJhbmtzLXRydXN0LWZpcnN0LXJlcHVibGljLXdpdGgtdGhlaXItbW9uZXk_Y21waWQ9=
QkJEMDMyMDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR=
0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzIwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB2bd764ad" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">  turning safe deposits into risky investments</a=
>.=C2=A0If the investments end up being worth less than the deposits, then =
regulators and central banks step in and there is some sort of rushed rescu=
e to make sure that the depositors still get paid.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One important consequence of this is that the =
equity of the bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0the shareholders=E2=80=99 ownership stake=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0is just a tiny sliver resting on top of an enormous iceberg=
 of liabilities. In a good profitable conservative bank, there might be $10=
0 of assets, $90 of liabilities and thus $10 of equity. The liabilities are=
 certain and knowable, things like deposits that really need to be paid bac=
k at 100 cents on the dollar.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-=
1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impor=
tant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> The assets are risky and variable, and their valuation is a bit of a g=
uess: They include securities with volatile market prices, weird derivative=
s that are hard to value, and business loans with uncertain probabilities o=
f being paid back. The bank applies some accounting conventions and makes s=
ome guesses and comes up with a value of $100 for its assets,=C2=A0but ther=
e is a range of uncertainty around that number.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And because the equity is only like 10% of the=
 assets, if the asset valuation is off by 10%, then there is no more equity=
, and that=E2=80=99s bad. The value of the bank=E2=80=99s equity is=C2=A0<e=
m>extremely=C2=A0</em>sensitive to the value of its assets, because the ban=
k is so leveraged. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/30897493.258433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMTQtMTAtMTUvYmFuay1vZi1hbWVyaWNhLW1hZGUtMTY4LW1pbGxpb24tbGFzdC1xdWFydGV=
yLW1vcmUtb3ItbGVzcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzIwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYW=
lsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vb=
mV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB32887b9b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote once</a> that=
 =E2=80=9Ca=C2=A0bank is a collection of reasonable guesses about valuation=
. It is a purely statistical process. There is no objective reality. At bes=
t, there is a probability distribution, a reason to reject the null hypothe=
sis with some level of confidence.=E2=80=9D If the bank reports $100 of ass=
ets and $90 of liabilities, then=C2=A0<em>probably=C2=A0</em>its assets are=
 worth more than its liabilities, but you can=E2=80=99t really be=C2=A0<em>=
sure</em>. There is a cloud of probabilities, and $100 is in that cloud, bu=
t so are other numbers. Some of the other numbers are bad.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And most of the time the bank bops along like =
this, in its cloud of probabilities. But occasionally a thing will happen t=
o collapse the probabilities and force it to find a real number. Occasional=
ly a bank will have to, in effect, sell all its assets over a weekend. Ofte=
n the thing that causes this is=C2=A0<em>bad:=C2=A0</em>a bank run, a loss =
of confidence, an emergency. When this happens, the assets will probably se=
ll at a discount. If the discount is more than about 10% =E2=80=94=C2=A0mor=
e than the equity cushion =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the shareholders get nothing.=
 If you are in the sort of emergency that requires you to sell all of your =
assets over a weekend, it is arguably a little surprising to do=C2=A0<em>be=
tter=C2=A0</em>than a 10% discount.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse Group AG filed its <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30897493.258433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwNTMwOTIvMDAwMTM3MDM2ODIzMDAwMDI2L2=
NzLTIwMjIxMjMxLmh0bSNJZDAwMTMxMDc0Mg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1c9e5543" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> 2022 annual report</a> last week. It reported about 531 billion Swiss=
 francs of assets and about CHF 486 billion of liabilities, leaving about C=
HF 45 billion of shareholders=E2=80=99 equity (about 8.5% of assets). When =
it filed the report last week, its stock was trading at about CHF 2.24 per =
share, for a total market value of the stock of about CHF 9 billion (about =
$9.7 billion).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to put this is that the market thought=
 the stock was worth 20% of its book value.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> But another, more useful way to put it is that the market thought that=
 the=C2=A0<em>assets=C2=A0</em>were worth 93.2% of their book value: Credit=
 Suisse=E2=80=99s CHF 486 billion of liabilities were real enough, so if th=
e market priced the equity at CHF 9 billion then that implicitly meant that=
 it valued the assets at about CHF 495 billion. The market thought that the=
 reported asset value was off by 6.8%. But if the reported asset value was =
instead off by 8.5%, the stock would be worthless. The cushion was very ver=
y thin.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It kept getting thinner. Last Friday, the stoc=
k closed at CHF 1.86 per share, for a market value of CHF 7.4 billion. And =
over the weekend, Swiss authorities forced through a merger of Credit Suiss=
e and UBS Group AG. Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/30897493.258433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudWJzLmNvbS9nbG9iYWwvZW4vbWVkaWEvZ=
GlzcGxheS1wYWdlLW5kcC9lbi0yMDIzMDMxOS10cmVlLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B6128c30b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> UBS=E2=80=99s statement on the deal</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">UBS Chairman Colm Kelleher said: =
=E2=80=9CThis acquisition is attractive for UBS shareholders but, let us be=
 clear, as far as Credit Suisse is concerned, this is an emergency rescue.=
=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/30897493.258433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS5jb20vYWJv=
dXQtdXMtbmV3cy9lbi9hcnRpY2xlcy9tZWRpYS1yZWxlYXNlcy9jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLWFuZC1=
1YnMtdG8tbWVyZ2UtMjAyMzAzLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd38f30c4" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Axel P. Lehmann, Chairman of the B=
oard of Directors of Credit Suisse said: =E2=80=9CGiven recent extraordinar=
y and unprecedented circumstances, the announced merger represents the best=
 available outcome. This has been an extremely challenging time for Credit =
Suisse and while the team has worked tirelessly to address many significant=
 legacy issues and execute on its new strategy, we are forced to reach a so=
lution today that provides a durable outcome.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In deals like this, it is customary for the sh=
areholders of the selling bank to get something, not so much because their =
shares are worth much but because it is technically a voluntary deal, a mer=
ger between a willing buyer and a willing seller, and it is hard for the bo=
ard of directors of the selling company to say to their shareholders =E2=80=
=9Chey we negotiated the best possible price for you, which is zero.=E2=80=
=9D This is only technically true, though, and you can tell from Lehmann=E2=
=80=99s statement that Credit Suisse was not exactly a willing seller. It w=
as barely even involved in the deal: =E2=80=9C[Credit Suisse Chief Executiv=
e Officer Ulrich]=C2=A0Koerner and the rest of the Credit Suisse management=
 team were marginalized as emergency weekend talks =E2=80=94=C2=A0led by Sw=
iss National Bank=C2=A0President=C2=A0Thomas Jordan=C2=A0=E2=80=94 to sell =
the group to UBS gathered pace,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/30897493.258433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9u=
ZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjAvY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS11YnMtdGFrZW92ZXItaG93LWE=
tMTY2LXllYXItb2xkLWJhbmstY29sbGFwc2VkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMjAyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJn=
V0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDMyMCZ1d=
G1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB11765646" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  reports Bloomberg</a>.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is a payment, in stock, of one UBS s=
hare for every 22.48 Credit Suisse shares. UBS closed on Friday at CHF 17.1=
1 per share, making the deal worth about CHF 0.76 per Credit Suisse share, =
or about CHF 3 billion total, down about 60% from Friday=E2=80=99s close. I=
 have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30897493.258=
433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDg=
vYmluYW5jZS1zLXpoYW8tc2JmLWVkLWZ0eC1zLWJhbmttYW4tZnJpZWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyMD=
IzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX=
3Rlcm09MjMwMzIwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1e=
2a1caa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">  previously described</a> the customary payment for equity=
 in deals like this as =E2=80=9Ca Snickers bar,=E2=80=9D and given that ben=
chmark Credit Suisse drove a surprisingly hard bargain. <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30897493.258433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjAvY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS11YnMtdGFr=
ZW92ZXItaG93LWEtMTY2LXllYXItb2xkLWJhbmstY29sbGFwc2VkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMjAyM19=
NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZX=
JtPTIzMDMyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC11765=
646" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  Bloomberg again</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When the terms of the initial UBS offer =E2=80=
=94 which valued its rival at just 1 billion francs =E2=80=94 landed on Sun=
day morning, the Credit Suisse managers were outraged. The price tag was se=
en as derisory for a bank that had a market cap of $8 billion at the close =
on Friday. Shareholders would be wiped out, managers argued.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Saudi National Bank =E2=80=94 the Swiss bank=
=E2=80=99s largest shareholder =E2=80=94 urged Credit Suisse to reject the =
offer. Calls went out from Credit Suisse to various institutions, including=
 Deutsche Bank AG, in a last-ditch attempt to find an alternative. But the =
complexity and timeframe meant there were no takers. A full sale to UBS was=
 the only option. That triggered a final round of back-and-forth which lift=
ed the price to 0.76 francs per share. That's 99% lower than Credit Suisse'=
s peak share price.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can, on the internet, find various express=
ions of astonishment that a bank as old and important as Credit Suisse turn=
ed out to be worth only $3 billion.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foo=
tnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> But this is, I think, the wrong way to look at it. Credit Suisse is no=
t worth $3 billion; it is worth half a trillion dollars, more or less.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> It's just that virtually all of that value =E2=80=94=C2=A0more than 99=
% of it =E2=80=94=C2=A0belongs to its creditors. UBS will take over Credit =
Suisse=E2=80=99s hundreds of billions of assets and use them to pay Credit =
Suisse=E2=80=99s hundreds of billions of liabilities, and there's the tinie=
st sliver =E2=80=94=C2=A0about $3 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0left for its share=
holders. That $3 billion is pretty much rounding error on the value of Cred=
it Suisse; it could just as well have been $5 billion, or $1 billion, or a =
Toblerone bar. The value and mechanics of this deal don=E2=80=99t depend th=
at much on the=C2=A0<em>price for the equity</em>, as you can tell by the f=
act that UBS=C2=A0<em>tripled=C2=A0</em>that price in the course of a few h=
ours.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It really could just as well have been zero, b=
ut it is polite to give the shareholders <em>something</em>, a little conso=
lation prize on their way out the door. The dynamics are:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You want shareholders to get somethin=
g so that the board of Credit Suisse can feel okay about agreeing to the de=
al, rather than making=C2=A0trouble and trying to hold out for something be=
tter.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You want shareholders =
to get something so that they don=E2=80=99t make=C2=A0legal=C2=A0trouble, t=
rying to find some legal way to block the deal. (My Bloomberg Opinion colle=
ague Shuli Ren <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/308=
97493.258433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMj=
MtMDMtMjAvY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS1hdDEtYm9uZGhvbGRlcnMtZmluZC1vdXQtbGlmZS1zLXVuZ=
mFpcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzIwMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3Vy=
Y2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB77eb12b4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  writes</a>: =E2=80=9CRegulators m=
ight have just given Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s equity owners some sweeteners =
so they don=E2=80=99t go to court and overturn the merger.=E2=80=9D)</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You want shareholders to get something=
 so that they are more willing to support the combined bank, and the bankin=
g system generally, after the merger. If you make Saudi National Bank and o=
ther big holders feel like they have been taken care of, even a little bit =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0even with 90% losses =E2=80=94=C2=A0they might be a bit more=
 willing to buy bank shares in the future, and it does feel like banks are =
going to be selling a lot of shares in the future.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">You want shareholders to get something because the=C2=A0<e=
m>employees=C2=A0</em>often own a lot of shares, and you need them to keep =
coming to work, and zeroing them is bad for morale. Not that a 90% haircut =
isn=E2=80=99t, but 100% is worse.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly, it is normally a requirement in mer=
gers for the selling shareholders to get to vote on the deal: They own the =
company, after all, and it can=E2=80=99t be bought from them without their =
permission. But in a distressed bank merger it is silly to pretend that the=
 shareholders own the company, and nobody did. =E2=80=9CPursuant to the eme=
rgency ordinance which is being issued by the Swiss Federal Council,=E2=80=
=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30897493.25843=
3/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS5jb20vYWJvdXQtdXMtbmV3cy9lbi9hcnRpY2xlc=
y9tZWRpYS1yZWxlYXNlcy9jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLWFuZC11YnMtdG8tbWVyZ2UtMjAyMzAzLmh0=
bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCd38f30c4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> says Credit Suisse</a>,=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Cthe merger can be implemented without approval of the sharehold=
ers.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The upshot of this for UBS is not that it paid=
 CHF 3 billion to buy its historic competitor. The upshot of this is that i=
t has assumed hundreds of billions of francs of liabilities, and taken on a=
 bunch of assets that are probably worth more than that, but it=E2=80=99s h=
ard to tell over a weekend, or ever really. Fortunately <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30897493.258433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTkvdGhlLW9uZS1iaWctd2lubmVyLWFu=
ZC1tYW55LWxvc2Vycy1vZi11YnMtcy1jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLXJlc2N1ZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzI=
wMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG=
1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
bdf9b5fc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">  it got a discount</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[UBS CEO] Ralph Hamers =E2=80=A6 a=
nd his team will have plenty to work through as they consider which busines=
ses and people to keep, alter or jettison. But he=E2=80=99ll have 56 billio=
n francs of so-called badwill to help cover any writedowns, as well as 9 bi=
llion francs of guarantees from the Swiss government to take on certain los=
ses. And the firm can access a huge liquidity line from the central bank.=
=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The badwill is the difference between the pric=
e that UBS paid for the assets and their book value. In Credit Suisse=E2=80=
=99s accounting, it had CHF 531 billion of assets as of Dec. 31; UBS effect=
ively bought them for CHF 473 billion.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#=
footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: no=
ne !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bl=
ock;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> If Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s valuation was too high by 10%, then UBS sti=
ll makes out okay.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course banks aren=E2=80=99t allowed to oper=
ate with=C2=A0<em>too=C2=A0</em>thin a sliver of equity, and UBS will have =
to make sure that its capital ratios are high enough to support the new muc=
h larger bank. After the deal, =E2=80=9Cthe bank remains capitalized well a=
bove its target of 13%,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/30897493.258433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudWJzLmNvbS9nbG9iYWwvZW4vbWVk=
aWEvZGlzcGxheS1wYWdlLW5kcC9lbi0yMDIzMDMxOS10cmVlLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cC6128c30b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">UBS announced</a>, while <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30897493.258433/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmlubWEuY2gv=
ZW4vbmV3cy8yMDIzLzAzLzIwMjMwMzE5LW1tLWNzLXVicy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB23=
b6b18f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> Swiss regulators announced</a> that =E2=80=9Cthe takeover =
will result in a larger bank, for which the current regulations require hig=
her capital buffers,=E2=80=9D but they =E2=80=9Cwill grant appropriate tran=
sitional periods for these to be built up.=E2=80=9D Now UBS owns Credit Sui=
sse; it would like to be able to hang onto it.</p>
