<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">AT1s</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After the 2008 financial crisis, European bank=
s issued a lot of what are called =E2=80=9Cadditional tier 1 capital securi=
ties,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Ccontingent convertibles,=E2=80=9D or AT1s or CoC=
os. The way an AT1 works is like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It is a bond, has a fixed face amount=
, and pays regular interest.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>It is perpetual =E2=80=94=C2=A0the bank never has to pay it back =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but the bank can pay it back after five years, and generally does.</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If the bank=E2=80=99s common equity =
tier 1 capital ratio =E2=80=94=C2=A0a measure of its regulatory capital =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0ffalls below 7%, then the AT1 is=C2=A0<em>written down to zero:=
=C2=A0</em>It never needs to be paid back; it just goes away completely.</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This =E2=80=94=C2=A0a =E2=80=9C7% trigger perm=
anent write-down AT1=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 is not the only way for an AT1 to w=
ork, though it is the way that Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s AT1s worked. Some AT=
1s have different triggers. Some AT1s=C2=A0<em>convert into common stock </=
em>when the trigger is hit, instead of being written down to zero; others a=
re <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30897493.258433=
/aHR0cHM6Ly9qbmYudWZtLmVkdS9jZ2kvdmlld2NvbnRlbnQuY2dpP2FydGljbGU9MTAwMCZjb2=
50ZXh0PWpvdXJuYWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBecc59f03" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  <em>temporar=
ily=C2=A0</em>written down</a> (they stop paying interest) when the trigger=
 is hit, but can bounce back if the equity recovers. (Here is a 2013 <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30897493.258433/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmlzLm9yZy9wdWJsL3F0cnBkZi9yX3F0MTMwOWYucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBcef1d6ee" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> primer on CoCos</a> from the Bank for International S=
ettlements.)=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These securities are, basically, a trick. To=
=C2=A0<em>investors</em>, they seem like bonds: They pay interest, get paid=
 back in five years, feel pretty safe. To=C2=A0<em>regulators,=C2=A0</em>th=
ey seem like equity: If the bank runs into trouble, it can raise capital by=
 zeroing the AT1s. If investors think they are bonds and regulators think t=
hey are equity, somebody is wrong. The investors are wrong.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In particular, investors seem to think that AT=
1s are=C2=A0<em>senior=C2=A0</em>to equity, and that the common stock needs=
 to go to zero before the AT1s suffer any losses. But this is not quite rig=
ht. You can tell=C2=A0because the whole point of the AT1s is that they=C2=
=A0go to zero if the common equity tier 1 capital ratio falls below 7%. Lik=
e, imagine a bank:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It has $1 billion of assets (also $1 b=
illion of regulatory risk-weighted assets).<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It has $100 million of common equ=
ity (also $100 million of regulatory common equity tier 1 capital).</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It has a 10% CET1 capital ratio.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It also has $50 million of AT1s with a 7% =
write-down trigger, and $850 million of more senior liabilities.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This bank runs into trouble and the value of i=
ts assets falls to $950 million. What happens? Well, under the very straigh=
tforward terms of the AT1s =E2=80=94=C2=A0not some weird fine print in the =
back of the prospectus, but=C2=A0<em>right in the name </em>=E2=80=9C7% CET=
1 trigger write-down AT1=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0this is what happens:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It has $950 million of assets and $50 =
million of common equity, for a CET1 ratio of 5.3%.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">This is below 7%, so the AT1s are triggered and written d=
own to zero.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now it has $950 milli=
on of assets, $850 million of liabilities, and thus $100 million of shareho=
lders=E2=80=99 equity.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now it has =
a CET1 ratio of 10.5%: The writedown of the AT1s has restored the bank=E2=
=80=99s equity capital ratios.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This, again, is very explicitly the whole thin=
g that the AT1 is supposed to do,=C2=A0this is its main function, this is t=
he AT1 working exactly as advertised. But notice that in this simple exampl=
e the bank has $950 million of assets, $850 million of liabilities and $100=
 million of shareholders=E2=80=99 equity. This means that=C2=A0<em>the comm=
on stock still has value</em>. The common shareholders still own shares wor=
th $100 million, even as the AT1s are now permanently worth zero.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>The AT1s are junior to the common stock</e=
m>. Not all the time, and there are scenarios (instant descent into bankrup=
tcy) where the AT1s get paid ahead of the common. But the most basic functi=
on=C2=A0of the AT1=C2=A0is to go to zero while the bank is a going concern =
with positive equity value, meaning that its function is to go to zero befo=
re the common stock does.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse has issued a bunch of AT1s over =
the years; as of last week it had about CHF 16 billion outstanding. Here is=
